# 5. Observations & Conclusions

### 5.1 Transfer Attack Immunity
All three GIT-Large variants show near-complete immunity to ResNet50 transfer attacks at ε = 8/255 and substantial resistance at ε = 16/255 when measured against ground truth. This is due to the fundamental architectural difference between CNN (ResNet50) and Vision Transformer (GIT-Large) — adversarial perturbations crafted to exploit convolutional filter responses do not generalise to patch-based attention mechanisms.

### 5.2 White-Box Vulnerability
Both fine-tuned models significantly outperform the base model under white-box attacks. Base MI-FGSM BLEU-4 drop is 28.9%, versus 12.5% (LoRA) and 11.2% (Full FT) — representing a ~57-61% improvement in robustness.

### 5.3 LoRA is the Recommended Defense
LoRA and Full FT achieve nearly identical robustness, but LoRA retains substantially more clean-image performance. Full fine-tuning reduces clean BLEU-4 by 55.6% vs base; LoRA reduces it by only 38.3%. For practical deployment where both robustness and caption quality matter, LoRA adversarial fine-tuning is the superior choice.

### 5.4 Self-Reference vs Ground Truth Evaluation
The large self-reference drops under transfer attacks (~67-78% BLEU drop) should not be interpreted as severe caption degradation — they reflect minor phrasing variations between the model's clean and attacked outputs. Ground truth evaluation shows the actual impact is much smaller (< 2% BLEU drop at ε = 8/255).

